2026-03-04 10:03:29,708 - trading_bot.agents - WARNING - Devil's Advocate VETOED emergency trade: DO NOT PROCEED. The pre-mortem reveals four compounding structural flaws that were obscured by superficially independent evidence clustering: (1) CROWDED TRADE RISK IS TERMINAL — COT at 99th percentile Managed Money longs is not merely a 'near-term technical factor' as dismissed in the reasoning; it is the single most historically reliable contrary indicator in soft commodity markets. We are buying into maximum crowding. If the trade goes wrong for ANY reason — including reasons we haven't anticipated — the exit door is a fire escape. (2) CRITICAL DATA DISCREPANCY IGNORED — The technical agent reports 200-day SMA at 294.46 while the reasoning memo states 328.85. This is a 34-point discrepancy on a key resistance level. If the 200-day SMA is actually 294.46 (not 328.85), the 'oversold recovery' framing changes entirely — price at 290.47 is already nearly AT the 200-day, not 13.9% below it. This error may have materially inflated the bullish recovery narrative. (3) EVIDENCE INDEPENDENCE IS OVERSTATED — The five 'independent' bullish signals share a common dependency: they are all conditioned on geopolitical/weather disruptions persisting. If ONE resolves (Hormuz, Santos, Copán), the evidence cluster collapses non-linearly, not proportionally. True independence would require signals that are orthogonal even under stress scenarios. (4) WEIGHTED CONSENSUS OF 0.56 IS BELOW ANY RATIONAL ENTRY THRESHOLD — The framework itself acknowledges this falls well below the 0.85 strong-signal threshold. A 0.56 consensus with 6 existing positions in KC and a VaR utilization that, while stated at 0%, presumably reflects mark-to-market rather than tail-risk on a 36.37% IV instrument, means the risk-adjusted expected value is negative after transaction costs and volatility drag. The honesty embedded in the PLAUSIBLE (not PROVEN) designation should be respected: PLAUSIBLE trades do not justify new entries in already-crowded soft commodity futures. If determined to express this view, the ONLY defensible structure is a defined-risk long call spread (not outright futures) with maximum loss capped at 1% of portfolio, entered after COT positioning normalizes below the 80th percentile — which is not today's setup.
